-- SE Asia Stocks - Indonesia falls for 2nd day, foreign investors sell
-- By Viparat Jantraprap
-- Wed Aug 06, 2014 06:52AM EDT
-- None



BANGKOK, Aug 6 (Reuters) - Stocks in Indonesia underperformed in Southeast Asia on Wednesday amid outflows and losses in large caps and Thai shares retreated from a more than one-week high on the previous session as shares of CP All <CPALL.BK> fell before it reported quarterly earnings.

Selling in large cap Bank Rakyat Indonesia <BBRI.JK> and Astra International <ASII.JK> sent the benchmark Jakarta SE Composite Index <.JKSE> 1 percent lower, its second consecutive day of fall. Foreign investors offloaded shares worth a net 1.2 trillion rupiah ($102.17 million), a second straight day, stock exchange data showed. Thai SET index <.SETI> edged down 0.4 percent, led down by a 1.1 percent drop in shares of CP All. The country's largest convenience store chain reported a 15 percent drop in quarterly net profit after the market close. [ID:nL4N0QB1HB]